betterquesting:10.desc:8: The main purpose for this device is to turn Certus Quartz Crystals into Charged Certus Quartz.
Turns crystal seeds into Pure Crystals.

LV Batteries were very simple to make, but more effective forms of power storage will be more complex to build, so we'll need to lay the groundwork now.

Tiny Piles of Antimony can be obtained by centrifuging Impure Stibnite Dust. 9 tiny piles makes a dust.

Welcome to Omnifactory!

§2This pack is intended to be played in an Lost Cities / Overworld dimension.

§3If you wish to build your base in a skyblock world, place the Void World Cake down on the ground, and eat a slice to be sent to the void. Please note that you'll still need to return to the  Lost Cities / Overworld dimension to mine, but you can freely build in complete safety in the Void World.

§c§rOres in this pack exist solely in large clusters, or 'veins'. These veins are scattered randomly around the world, and are relatively common. The Scanner in your inventory can detect any ore within 16 blocks of you, so digging down and scanning should show you any nearby veins. Try scanning now to see if there are any surface deposits near you.

The Scanner does have limited energy, but you should be able to build a Wired Charger to gain the ability to recharge it long before you are close to running out of energy.

In order to proceed, you'll need to locate a source of Iron. You have a few options. Magnetite veins are higher up and contain large amounts of iron, as well as some vanadium and gold. Another good source of iron is Limonite veins, which contain several types of iron. Finally, Pyrite can be found paired with copper in several types of veins.

Wrought Iron is obtained simply by smelting Iron a second time. It has more durability than Iron, so it is better for making tools, but do not convert your entire Iron supply over to Wrought Iron. The two materials are not interchangable and you'll need Iron or Wrought Iron as demanded by various recipes.

Mining Hammers offer a relatively cheap way to mine out areas much faster. They clear a 3x3 of blocks and mine quickly, and are absolutely worth investing your first few ingots of metal into.

Stone is the cheapest Mining Hammer, but naturally it breaks quickly. Since you have some Iron already, consider using those on your first few mining expeditions.

The best Mining Hammers are Diamond and Platinum. Other Mining Hammers are also good but wear out more quickly.

Before you continue, you'll need access some more materials.

Redstone: Found only deep in the world, paired with Cinnibar and Ruby.

Copper: Two primary sources. Tetrahedrite veins are higher up, while Chalcopyrite veins are lower. Paired with some small amounts of iron. You'll also find Malechite inside of Iron veins, this is another type of copper ore.

Tin: Found essentially at ground level, and almost always detectable by scanner from the surface. Cassiterite is another type of tin ore, and they're always found together. If you cannot find a vein of tin, there are small amounts of tin inside veins of aluminium and rock salt, which might be enough to hold you over until you find a proper tin vein.

Coal: Found in relatively shallow depths. Lignite Coal is just a less pure and less effective form of Coal.

Gold: Found inside of Magnetite veins, close to the surface.

The most basic cables, such as these, can be wrapped in their rubber insulation by hand. Later on, with more advanced types of cables, you'll need to use an Assembler and liquid Rubber to perform this, but you can do it the easy way for now.
With all of the many components in place, its time to merge them together into a single circuit. Go ahead and craft a§e Microprocessor§r.

In most expert packs, you want to try to process as little ore as possible before you get access to ore doubling. Its a habit most of us are in.

You shouldn't feel any pressure to do that in Omnifactory, though. Ore veins are massive, and mining is extremely fast with Mining Hammers. What's more, even once you get access to the Macerator, it processes ore extremely slowly, and takes a decent amount of power as well.

Obvious exceptions would be rare materials like Gold, or anything you need to buy from the coin shop because you can't find it. Those are worth doubling, naturally.

But at least for now, you shouldn't feel any guilt about processing the more common ores without doubling them! Ore doubling can be safely ignored until MV or even later.

A 'substrate' is the 'board' part of a circuit board... the backing that the circuit components and wires are laid into. A good substrate needs to not conduct electricity, for obvious reasons. Wood coated in rubber is a primitive but relatively effective material to use as your first substrate.

You'll also need to make Vacuum Tubes, as well as some primitive Resistors. Paper will work as a material for these, for now.

Make sure to code these recipes into a Workbench... you'll be making a LOT of these things.

One of the eccentricities of the pack you'll need to get used to is the way the tools are displayed. Most tools can be made out of nearly any metal, and JEI will display a huge number of options... every combination of every tool with every material. However, the pattern to make the tool is always identical, so just arrange the plates and ingots in the same manner as the examples, ignoring whatever material it says. Rods where rods go, plates where plates, etc. The only restriction is that tools must be made from all of the same material... you cannot mix and match different metals in a single item.

Recipes will default to showing a 'Darmstadtium' tool (or sometimes Aluminium) of the appropriate type if a tool is required, but the correct type of tool made out of any metal will work. So just ignore the tool's material in the recipes, it can be whatever you'd like.

For now, make a Hammer (not a Mining Hammer, mind you... six ingots, not five). Hammers can be used to turn two ingots into one plate. Plates can make a File, Files can make Rods, etc. Use JEI to work your way down the list of tools. It is §oSTRONGLY§r encouraged to encode these patterns into a Worktable to be able to quickly make new tools, otherwise it will become tedious quickly.

Wrought Iron is probably your best bet for a tool material right now, but better materials will become available as you progress.

If you try to craft each item as you realize you need it, you'll go insane. It is recommended that you use Worktables to encode in production chains for things like tools, circuits, machine casings, and more. If you're doing things right, you'll likely have a dozen or more worktables in short order.

Load up the table's storage area with the necessary materials, and batch craft items when needed. The satisfaction of clicking one button and getting 12 circuits is worth the setup.
Iron Furnaces can smelt an item in 150 ticks, which is somewhat faster than a Stone Furnace, which takes 200 ticks. The fuel efficiency remains the same for all furnaces.
Copper Furnaces are another step up in speed, taking 100 ticks to smelt an item.
Silver Furnaces are another step up in speed, taking a mere 60 ticks to smelt an item.
Gold Furnaces are yet another step up in speed, taking only 40 ticks to smelt an item.

While Obsidian Furnaces are the same speed as Diamond Furnaces, they have twice the throughput since they can smelt two items at once.

You may find that Diamond Furnaces suit your needs better than Obsidian, but they'll both be crafting ingredients in various machines soon enough, so crafting one is not a waste, even if you don't use it.
No more grinding up metals into dusts and mixing them. Plus, many of the more complex alloys are now possible.
Diamond Furnaces are the fastest available, taking only 25 ticks to smelt an item.
Steel is a basic component in all sorts of machines and alloys.

The main function of this oven is to increase the fuel values of your wood and coal while also recovering some of the various potentially useful waste products.

Turning Coal into Coal Coke will not only make it more useful as fuel, but also produce Phenol, which you'll need for circuits.

You'll need Obsidian to make Dark Steel. Most of the tools you can make cannot mine Obsidian, but you do have a few potential options for ones that will work. The options you're most likely to have access to at this point are:

1) A Diamond Pickaxe or Diamond Mining Hammer.

2) A Platinum Mining Hammer (not pickaxe though).

3) A Cobalt Pickaxe (smelted from Cobaltite).

Your first major crafting project!

You'll need a small bit of Silver for this dynamo. If you haven't found a Galena vein yet (which is where Silver is), then consider buying some Silver using Omnicoins. You won't need a ton of silver and lead just yet, so it won't bankrupt you.

This quest is repeatable once per hour and gives you a free cake to the Void World or Overworld. You can also refill your cakes with the items indicated in their tooltips.

§dNote: Travel to the Void World appears to be bugged for many players. The issue is being worked on. If you can't get the Void Cake to work right, you can simply play in Lost Cities or Overworld instead without issue... lack of access to the Void World will not block your progression in any way.
Steel alloyed with Obsidian makes Dark Steel, which is needed for many of the machines in EnderIO and Applied Energistics.
The place for your very first chemical reactions, namely making some improved substrates.

Later on, Uraninite Dust will be able to be used for a source of Uranium and Radon, but for now, you can smelt it into Pulsating Dust, a mysterious magical material that taps into the power of Ender. Pulsating Dust has all sorts of strange and potentially dangerous applications, including the ability to make Pulsating Ingots and Ender Pearls.

An EnderIO alloy.

Made from Pulsating Dust and an Iron Ingot.

Puslating Dust can also be combined with a Diamond to make an Ender Pearl.

An EnderIO alloy.

Made from Silicon Dust and a Steel Ingot.
Stores a huge amount of RF power.
Stores a large amount of RF power.
Stores some RF power.

An EnderIO alloy.

Made from Energetic Blend and a Gold Ingot.
An EnderIO alloy.

Going out in search of a Rubber Tree is a viable option for sure. However, if this isn't appealing, you can also shear leaves and make Plantballs out of them. Plantballs smelt into Slime, and Slime smelts into Rubber.

You'll want to transition to Rubber Trees at some point, though, since the ratio of leaves to rubber is quite poor.

Rubber can be hammered into sheets just like metals can be turned to plates. Its quite inefficient to do it this way, but such is the life of early game Gregtech. At least rubber isn't particularly hard to come by.

With all of the many components in place, its time to merge them together into a single circuit. Go ahead and craft a §6Primitive Circuit§r.

This is where your Worktable setups will really shine! With the patterns encoded into a Worktable (well, really over many Worktables), you'll be able to batch craft circuits quickly. You'll be making a LOT of circuits, so you might as well invest the time into making them easily.

-----

With your first circuit in hand, you now want to build a CEF. The CEF is a device that converts RF power into EU power, which is what Gregtech machines need. CEFs come in two sizes, x4 and x16. Each slot can hold a single LV Battery. 

§o§4§cNEVER §rhook up a cable with a thickness less than the size of the CEF's the number of slots. So you must have a x4 cable for a 4 slot CEF, and a x16 Cable for a 16 slot Battery Buffer. Cables skinnier than the number of slots will cause the cable to burn up and be destroy

RF converts into EU at a 4 to 1 ratio. 100 RF becomes 25 EU, and vice versa. If you ever switch over to being primarily powered by EU, a device called the CEU can switch power from EU into RF.

The ultimate in local item transfer utility. Item conduits are fantastic and incredibly powerful.

Crafting them in an assembler instead of by hand gives twice as many conduits.
The most basic tier of RF energy conduits.
Conduits to carry even more RF power.
Conduits to carry even MORE RF power.
A tier two capacitor. Makes machines its put in run faster than just a basic capacitor.

Being able to fly is nice.

There's also a quest chain for Thermal Jetpacks (starting with the Leadstone Jetpack). Eventually you'll need to make both, but not for a long time, so feel free to ignore at least one of these quest chains unless you really really like flying.
Flying very fast is nice.
Flying even faster is nice.
Flying faster is nice.
These are the preferred way to move fluids around, rather than Gregtech pipes. Incredibly flexible and powerful, they'll make fluid crafting almost bearable.
Processor recipes have changed to require basic GT circuits instead of Redstone.
There's another machine you'll be needing before you get access to easier circuits, and that's the Cluster Mill, used to make foils.
The Wiremill is another major efficiency boost, giving you much greater yield for wires for your ingots.
When Ender Eyes just aren't creepy enough.

Among many many other functions, centrifuges can spin Impure Dusts to get not only the main dust, but also a tiny pile of a second dust. Often times, this is the only way to obtain more obscure material types.

So you have all the parts to power your machines, now to put it together.

Your Steam Dynamo needs burnable fuel (like Coal) and water. It will output RF power through the Excitation Coil (the red bit at the top). The orientation of the Steam Dynamo can be adjusted with a Crescent Hammer, if need be.

Although Energy Conduits can be used to transfer that RF power, it can also just simply be outputted directly into the next step, the CEF, by making the CEF touch the Excitation Coil.

The CEF will transform the power into EU. It needs to be fed RF powre to output its EU power through the red dot. The orientation can be adjusted using a Wrench. Then attach your Conductive Iron Cables to the red dot.

Now all you need is some Gregtech machines to hook up to the cables! You can make whatever you want, but its recommended that you get these two first:

The §6Wiremill§r will make crafting wires much, much easier.

The §6Compressor§r will make Plates from one ingot instead of two.

Not only are these faster than regular fluid conduits, they also have multiple channels. This makes it possible to have a large number of fluids moving over a single line. That will be useful for the more complicated chemistry projects later on.

Although there are several types of batteries you can make, Lithium Batteries are the best option by far, with the largest storage capacity and no downsides. Cadmium is second best, and Sodium is third.

Lithium is possible to find inside of Tungsten veins, however, they are fairly rare. Consider buying some Lithium from the coin store if you can't any (its in the bottom left corner-ish).

Cadmium is so tough to get at this point, its not even worth considering. However, Sodium is plentiful enough. You can get it by smelting Salt or Rock Salt, among other options. Just know that Sodium Batteries can only hold half the power of a Lithium Battery.

Nickel comes from several different ores, including Pentlandite and Garnierite, but they're all found in the same vein.

Nickel is used mostly for several very important alloys, including Invar and Cupronickel.

The Electric Blast Furnace is a major, major milestone in your Gregtech career. It has the power to smelt more advanced materials, the first of which, aluminium, is going to be important in the immediate future.

There is a diagram of how to build the EBF in JEI. The second and third levels must be a square shape of Coil Blocks (cupronickel is the only type of coil block you have access to for now), and the fourth level (the top) must be a 3x3 of Heatproof Machine Casings.

However, the first floor is very flexible. It all needs to be filled in, and the center of the 3x3 must be a Heatproof Machine Casing, but the rest is customizable. This quest calls for two energy hatches, a fluid input and output, and an item input and output, which is a total of six positions. Their specific order and placement don't matter, as long as they're in the first level and on the outside.

The seventh position will be the EBF controller, which leaves one free. You could put in a filler Heatproof Machine Casing, or a third energy input.

You'll most likely want to locate your batteries quite near to the EBF. It is very power hungry, and if it cannot get enough energy, progress on the current item smelting will start to regress. If it reaches zero, your inputs are lost, so be very careful to ensure the EBF has enough power when you go to smelt things.

Including a Gem Sensor on a Microminer mission will make the machine primarily collect gems instead of ores.

Doesn't work with all tiers.
Access all of your items on a single screen. Soon, anyway.
Once you have this and a storage cell, you can start getting digital.

A 1k Storage Cell. Unfortunately, its limited to only being able to store 63 types of items, but it will still help with storage issues enormously. If you want more than 63 types, you'll need to get an ME Drive and multiple Storage Cells.

The 4k Storage Cell demands Inscribed Processors, which will need to wait for more advanced technology.

Although most alloys require an Alloy Smelter, some alloys can be made simply by mixing the correct metal dusts together. 

Copper Dust mixed with Redstone Dust makes Red Alloy Dust.

Iron Dust mixed with Redstone Dust makes Conductive Iron Dust.

Smelt it into ingots, hammer it into Plates, and cut them into Wires.
A tier three capacitor.

Used to store liquid experience.

You can set it to auto-output in a direction facing into any machine that needs experience, and it will pump the XP in.

With your EBF running, start to create a supply of Aluminium ingots. If you find your power supply is faltering, you may want to add additional boilers and turbines. However, you're also about to unlock MV power, so perhaps you'll want to wait until MV for more powerful turbines.
MV Batteries function essentially the same as LV Batteries, only stronger. They also need to be put into an MV CEF or MV Battery Buffer.
An MV Electrolyzer opens up many options that were previously closed. You have significantly easier ways to produce aluminium, oxygen, lithium, antimony, and a huge number of other dusts and gasses.

Assembling Machines are the linchpin of your factory, gating progression through the circuits.

Building one will enable you to craft large amounts of circuits very easily.
Though more expensive, ME Conduits have the advantage of being able to share a block space with other conduit types.

Nether Quartz is found in Quartzite veins in the Overworld. Nether Quartz in an Electrolyzer gives you Crushed Black Quartz, and you need an Autoclave to get the actual crystal you need.

Black Quartz and Aluminium Plates will make Aluminium Casings, which are your first steps into a mod called Actually Additions.
The Machine Block is the first step towards opening up a mod called Extra Utilities 2.

Your first Tier Two Circuits will require four Tier One Circuits plus some Gallium to craft.

Prioritizing getting a cheaper way to get Tier Two Circuits is the goal, since these circuits are very costly to make.
Exquisite Gems can be cut down into multiple flawless, and then regular gems using the Cutting Machine if so desired.

Electrolyzing Sphalerite is the way to get Gallium. The Zinc and Sulfur will be quite useful as well.

Sphalerite spawns in Zinc veins.

If you're having trouble getting the quest to complete, check to see if you have small piles or tiny piles. If you have small piles, combine them together into a full pile then break it down into tiny. A workbench can help with this to click through multiple possible recipes.

Cuts things up.

Filling it up with plain Water will work fine for anything you want to process.

You can also use Distilled Water or Lubricant, which speeds up the processing and therefore reduces energy consumed, but the benefit is rather minor compared the extra affort to make those fluids instead of just plain water. Something to keep in mind for the future though.

You might consider waiting until you have Electronic Processors before progressing too far down the path of MV machines, since these circuits are much easier to make than Primtive Processors.

A hefty amount of Silicon Dust and power will net you a Silicon Boule, the starting point for advanced wafers.

Make sure your power system is up to the task. You'll need an enormous buffer of energy.
You'll be needing huge amounts of these Wafers eventually, and they take a while, so consider doing some batch crafting at some point.

Phenol is produced as a byproduct from making Coal Coke in a Pyrolyse Oven.

These boards will enable a much cheaper method of circuit production.
Turns your Wafers into various types of chips wafers.
It takes quite a while to etch these. Batch crafting would be smart.
Back through the Cutting Machine to make individual chips.

Much easier to mass produce than Primitive Circuits, and fulfill the same function in nearly all cases.

You should be batch crafting these.
Three Electronic Circuits and various other components will create an Electronic Processor.

You'll need a variety of lenses for use in the Precision Laser Engraver, all of which are made in the Autoclave, along with Water.

Initially you'll need a Red Lens, a Diamond Lens, and a Glass Lens.

A Red Lenses can be made from Almandine, Ruby, Red Garnet, Jasper or Rutile.

The other two lenses should be self evident.

Your first tier three circuit.

As you'll realize is the pattern, it is expensive and unwieldy to make, but this incentivises getting access to the later tier three circuits, which are much easier to mass produce.
Chrome is obtained by electrolyzing Ruby Dust.
The Farmer can be used to automate the planting and gathering of a variety of crops, including Potatos, Canola, Carrots and Beetroot.
Sulfuric Acid is produced from Sulfur and Water. You'll need huge amounts of this for a whole range of chemical reactions, as it is a very common ingredient.

Ethanol and Sulfuric Acid make Ethylene.

Ethylene and Oxygen make Polyethylene.

When you have large amounts of Rutile (probably after you visit the Moon) you can consider using it to improve your Polyethylene yields. For now its not a great idea, as Rutile is quite rare.
A Fluid Solidifer and a Plate Mold will get you the sheets you need.

If you didn't know, you can have stacks of items stored inside of an Interface. Placing a Storage Bus onto the Interface lets you access and use those items in recipes. And putting a Crafting Card inside the Interface will let the Interface automatically place autocraft orders for items it is lacking. This is the best way to keep basic components in stock so you don't have to wait for them to be crafted, especially things like wafers, circuits and rods.

Stainless Steel will be your primary material for HV, in the same way that Aluminium was for MV and Wrought Iron was for LV.

Manganese comes from electrolyzing Tantalite Dust, Pyrolusite or Spessartine Dust. You already have Chrome.

Mix up a bunch of the dust in a Mixer and begin processing it through the Blast Furnace. This may be a good time to reevaluate your power generation and storage infrastructure.
With Einsteinium, you've got everything you need to make a few peices of Omnium.
Diamond Plate, Silicon Plate and a basic Circuit.
With this bad boy, you can store a virtually unlimited number of items inside a single block, and search through them all. You might need more Storage Cells though.
Gold Plate, Silicon Plate and a basic Circuit.
Go find them in meteors, or etch them yourself.
Encode recipes into these for automation.
Certus Plate, Silicon Plate and a basic Circuit.
Terminal to encode patterns.
The Atomic Reconstructor uses RF Power to change items into other items.
So you don't have to run to your Interfaces each time you make a new pattern.
You'll be making a lot of these, if you're playing the pack right.

Autocrafting at last.

Well, you need patterns too I guess.
Crafting in a digital grid is heaven after using primitive wooden tables for however long.
Coal can be turned into Void Crystals, and Iron can be turned into Enori Crystals.
The Resonator is one of the primary crafting methods for Extra Utilties 2. It requires Grid Power in order to function.

Grid Power explanation.

A Manual Mill is your only way of generating Grid Power at first.
Black Steel will be used to make various items within Extended Crafting.
Digital fluid storage.
Digital storage.
Digital storage.
Digital storage.
No Description
Digital fluid storage.
Digital fluid storage.
Digital fluid storage.

There are no diminishing returns on Grid Power, so feel free to build whatever types of generators you want to provide it for you.

Note that the individual generators have been balanced differently than normal, so take that into account before building 16 Watermills.

SMD components, or 'Surface Mounted Device' components, are one of the first endgame materials you'll be making. Even the mighty Tier Nine circuits require these components, and huge amounts of them. Its worthwhile to invest in an extremely robust system of automation for these components and all of their ingredients, since you'll never stop needing them. They will also work in place of the handmade components you've been using in all but the simplest of recipes.

All SMD components must be produced in at least an MV Assembing Machine, and they all will require liquid Polyethelyene. Start off with the SMD Transistor.
Next up are SMD Resistors, which are fairly simple.
You'll need Polyvinyl Chloride to make these.
Next up are SMD Diodes, which are fairly simple.

Annealed Copper is made in the Blast Furnace by treating Copper with Oxygen. It has less power loss than regular Copper when used as a cable, and is also required for more advanced electronic components.

Ethylene plus Chlorine makes Vinyl Chloride.

Vinyl Chloride and Oxygen makes Polyvinyl Chloride.

betterquesting:10.name:8: The Third And Final Tier One Circuits
betterquesting:10.desc:8: With all the SMD components ready, you can start to churn out Refined Circuits. These will be the tier one circuits you'll be using into the endgame, so get them fully automated and be ready to make them very easily in large numbers.
Better substrates.

Another electronic component.

Making it inside an Assembler is much, much cheaper than by hand.
Rare Earth comes from either centrifuging certain Impure Dusts, or processing those same Purified Dusts. The sources are essentially Redstone, and everything inside of a Bastnasite vein.
These Inscribers are much easier to work with for automation purposes than the usual ones, but might take a bit of experiementation to figure out how they work on your part.

While there are no types of veins that are extremely rare, its simply a mathematical reality that you'll almost certainly struggle to find at least one of the less common vein types. This isn't really avoidable.

But at this point, you've also most likely accumulated a fair number of Omnicoins from quest turn-ins. Do not be hesitant to spend them on the less common ores that you're lacking! 

Check the uses of various ores (generally the first one listed in JEI) to find the coin recipes for them.

Don't be a hoarder!

Gregtech machines are built from a number of componets, many of which are shared between the machines. Motors are used in a great number of recipes, even including other components. Make sure to encode this recipe into a Worktable. You'll be making them quite often.
Centrifuge enough Rare Earth and you'll get some Yttrium.
One of the more intricate components, an LV piston will be needed for a few machines.

Another common component of any machine that uses fluids.

You can use Paper Rings or Rubber Rings, but both will require a Knife to craft. A stick and a piece of flint will make a Knife with low durability, or check the recipe for metal ones.

Although you could magnetize Iron Bars by hand using Redstone, that's not an option for more advanced materials. This machine will let you magnetize Steel Rods, as well as even more advanced materials later.

There are no recipes for the Polarizer that require more than 32 volts, which means you can get away with using an LV Polarizer for the entire pack. However, higher voltages will work faster, in exchange for consuming more power.

Combining Titanium Tetrachloride with Magnesium in a Blast Furnace will net you your first Titanium Ingot.

But you'll need to cool it for it to be useful.
Rutile is not common on the Overworld, being containe inside Ilmenite Ore, and some in Bauxite Ore. Its found in much larger quantities on the Moon and other planets.
Rutile, Carbon and Chlorine makes Titanium Tetrachloride.
You'll need the higher tier Chemical Reactors to process Titanium.

With tier three circuits in hand, its time to make a Distillation Tower, which is the gatekeeper for both plastic and all the petrochemicals.

The Distillation Tower is a highly flexible multiblock structure, able to be anywhere from 2 blocks high to up to 15 high. The way that it works is that each level of the tower after the first will output an additional fluid output. Any fluid outputs that there are not room for are lost. What we need the Distillation Tower for right now is to break down Biomass Feedstock into Ethanol and Water. It only has two outputs, so a three high Distillation Tower is just fine, which is what the materials that the quest asks you for will build. However, if you're going to break down anything where you need more than the first two fluid outputs, like oil, make sure to increase the height of your tower to accomodate all of the outputs you want to keep. Also check the voltage requirements of the recipes, as many Distillation Tower recipes need higher voltages than MV. You can swap out your Energy Input for a higher tier one when that time comes.

The tower we'll be building at first is 3x3x3, with a hollow center. The controller goes center front of the bottom layer, with a Fluid Input Hatch in the middle of the bottom layer. An Output Bus and an Energy Input Hatch are also needed on the bottom level, and fill the rest in with Clean Stainless Steel Casings. Each level above that is a ring of 7 Clean Stainless Steel Casings, one Fluid Output and nothing in the center, except for the top most layer which needs another casing to fill in the center, to cap off the top.

betterquesting:10.name:8: The Fourth and Final Tier Five Circuits
Sulfuric Heavy, Light, Naphtha and Gas
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
Start off by running the Raw Oil through the Distillation Tower. This will result in you obtaining Sulfuric Heavy Fuel, Sulfuric Light Fuel, Sulfuric Naphtha, and Sulfuric Gas.

You'll need to come up with a system to sort and store these liquids, whether its manual handheld tanks, a system of multiblock tanks, or digital fluid storage.

Sulfuric Gas is converted into Refinery Gas by adding Hydrogen to it, just like all the other Sulfuric fuel types.

While Refinery Gas can be distilled further to break it down even more, it's probaby smartest for now to just burn it for power inside of a Gas Turbine.

However, you can marginally improve the amount of power you get by centrifuging the Refinery Gas, which will get you LPG (liquefied petroleum gas) and Methane. Both can still be burned inside a Gas Turbine, for more energy than the Refinery Gas would have gotten you. Even better, Methane will be needed for various other chemical reactions as well, so you can consider saving some and using it for that.

One of the easier ways to start getting Bio Diesel, the Canola Press uses RF power, unlike everything else in this area of the quest tree. Canola Oil can be burned for more RF power in an Oil Generator, or fermented into Refined Canola Oil in a Fermenter, or turned into Bio Diesel in a Chemical Reactor.

betterquesting:10.name:8: Seed Oil, Fish Oil, Canola Oil
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
A whole host of fluids can be used as the feedstock for your Biodiesel, including Seed Oil, Fish Oil, and the various tiers of Canola Oils.

Canola Oil is probably the easiest path.
Sulfuric Heavy Fuel is converted into Heavy Fuel by adding Hydrogen to it in a Chemical Reactor.
Sulfuric Light Fuel is converted into Light Fuel by adding Hydrogen to it in a Chemical Reactor.

Sulfuric Naphtha is turned into Naphtha by adding Hydrogen to it in a Chemical Reactor.

Naphtha can be burned for power, distilled down further into its components, or used to make Epoxid.

Please note that even if you prefer using Bio Diesel for power generation, you'll still need to do a bit of petrochem to get Naphtha for Epoxid.

Hydrogen Sulfide can be combined with Water to turn it into Sulfuric Acid, useful in many other petrochem reactions.

Or just void it all.

Diesel is a very popular choice for a primary power source in the midgame. While many of the liquids from previous steps could also potentially be burned for energy, its far more efficient to turn them into Diesel before burning them. And while Nitrodiesel is even better than Diesel, it takes so many extra steps that it might be wise to stop here, at least for now, and tackle Nitrodiesel later.

You'll need an MV Mixer to make Diesel, but once you have one, you just need to combine Light Fuel and Heavy Fuel in a 5 to 1 ratio.

An element paired exclusively with Platinum. If you haven't found a vein of Platinum yet, you'll need to buy Palladium as well.

Its smelted in the blast furnace, and it takes a while. Luckily you only need a tiny bit of it for now.
Water and Sodium make Sodium Hydroxide, an ingredient in Bio Diesel.

Air can be sent into the Vacuum Freezer to turn it into Liquid Air.

Liquid Air can be sent into a Cryogenic Distillation Tower to break it down into its components.

In addition to the components listed here, you'll need an Energy Input Hatch, a Fluid Input Hatch, and five Fluid Output Hatches, all of whatever size you wish.

Note that despite accepting EU power, Modular Machines will not overclock.

Bio Diesel is a decent renewable source of power that can potentially run your entire base, given enough crop production.

Please note that even if you prefer petrochem products to generate power, you'll need to do some Bio Diesel in order to get Glycerol, which is needed in Epoxid.

Nitrogen comprises 78% of the atmopshere. Because of this, within the first few loads of liquid air distillation, you'll have more Nitrogen than you know what to do with. Pretty soon you'll need to start voiding it.

Still, its quite useful for certain things, so always keep a bank of it around.
A Basic Air Colllector will suck up air at a decent rate, and you can then collect it as a fluid with a bucket or conduits. Make sure the front face is unobstructed.

Breaking down Noble Gasses into their components will require 53 full loads of Liquid Air to be processed. You'll be needing large quantities of the various Noble Gasses so you should get this automated and running now.
A simple combination of Nitrogen and Oxygen, the two most common elements in the air, yet this substance is very toxic. Chemistry is wierd.
Don't let the EPA catch you making this stuff.
This is the additive that will bring our diesel fuel to the next level.

The best and most powerful of the petrochemical fuels, Nitrodiesel is the premier choice for power in the midgame.

You'll need an HV Mixer to make it.
Acetic Acid and Sulfuric Acid make Ethenone.
There are several paths to Acetic Acid... probably the simplest is combining Oxygen, Hydrogen and Carbon, but one of the several other methods may appeal to you more. Check JEI.
A colorless liquid with a pungent, garlic-like odor, its needed in the production of Epoxid.

A Fiber Reinforced Epoxy Resin Sheet is made in a Chemical Bath, not a Chemical Reactor.

Other than that, its very similar to the other substrates you've made so far.

Its very, very easy to get overwhelmed by all of the petrochemical stuff in Gregtech, but doing the basics isn't very difficult, with a little bit of guidance. 

There are three types of oil that you'll find: Heavy Oil, Raw Oil, or Light Oil. Raw Oil (sometimes just called Oil in JEI) is something you can think of as 'Medium Oil'. Its a good starting point for Fuel, because it contains the ingredients for Fuel in roughly the correct ratios.

The next few quests will discuss how to turn Raw Oil into Fuel. Once you've mastered that, feel free to explore petrochem mechanics more with the basics down... there's no 'correct' way to do things in the end, and you can potentially power your base in dozens of different ways.

betterquesting:10.name:8: MV Energy Input And MV CEF
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
With Aluminium, you can replace the three LV Energy Input Hatches on your Electric Blast Furnace with a single MV one, if you want. When you're ready to move on to HV recipes in the EBF, you'll want to move up to HV Energy Input Hatches, and so on.

However, remember to keep the MV area seperate from your LV area. Hooking up an LV machine to MV current will result in the machine being destroyed! Also LV cables will burn up if you put MV current through them. That's why its probably best to keep the areas separate until you're comfortable and confident with voltages. Eventually you can use transformers to switch voltages within a single setup, but don't feel forced to try that until you've got a grasp on the basics.

All RF power is the same (it has no voltages), so you can use RF cables to route power from whereever you're generating and storing it to CEFs for each voltage. You don't have to use this setup, but its the most foolproof one for a beginner. And if you're an expert, well... you don't need my advice.

For your MV cables, you can use Copper to start with. Energetic Alloy cables are lossless, though, so consider them if you're able to mass produce those ingots.

An important wire for late game cables.

You'll need a Vacuum Freezer to cool the ingots before they can be used.

This is one of the simpler rockets you can build. The specifics of the shape don't really matter, as long as the rocket engines are on the bottom and all the parts are added. It also needs to be inside the edges of the Launch Pad and not taller than the Structure Tower. The Rocket Fluid Loader is a part of the rocket itself, and is where you insert the fuel, using buckets or conduits. Be careful, because it can continue to consume fuel even after the rocket is full up, and this will void the excess fuel.

§aIn order to progress this quest chain further, you'll first need to complete The Vat questline and the Rocket Fuel questline, both which are nearby on this page.
Marginally cheaper to make than Electronic Processor Arrays, and also the only way to make Refined Processor Mainframes.
At some point, in order to progress, you'll need to go into space. Making yourself a space suit is the first step towards that.

The Suit Workstation is needed to install Low Pressure Tanks (or a larger tank if you like) onto your Space Suit Chest-Piece.

Once installed, you can stand on a Gas Charging Pad to fill up the tanks with air. Of course, you'll need to fill the Gas Charging Pad with Oxygen first, probably via conduits.
Extended Crafting parts.
Extended Crafting parts.

Before you can build the rocket itself, you'll need a launch pad. The concrete part goes in a 3x3 flat on the ground. The Structure Tower is stacked in a column up into the air, with the lowest Structure Tower block being on the same Y-level as the launch pad blocks. With 6 blocks, you can only build a rocket 5 blocks high, due to having room for 5 blocks before hitting the top of the Structure Tower. This limitation can be bypassed by building more Structure Towers and stacking them even higher.

The Rocket Assembly Machine needs to go 1 block higher than the launch pad, so that the bottom of the Rocket Assemblyer is flush with the top of the launch pad. It also needs to be supplied with RF power to function.
With the Extended Crafting Table, you can now craft 5x5 recipes.
Even simple rockets demand Heavy Plates for their construction. In this case, made out of Steel.
You'll need this to set the Guidance Computer's destination to the Moon.

Shift + rightclick to warp forward a distance. Works through walls.

Powered with RF, and can be further enchanted on a Darksteel Anvil.

If you don't have one already, you'll need an Autoclave for the gem.

There isn't a ton going on, on the Moon's surface. You might be wondering why you bothered.

The biggest draw is that the blocks that make up the Moon's surface (Moon Turf) contains Deuterium, a substance otherwise difficult to get ahold of in large amounts. It will be very useful for the Modularium you'll need to make, as well as a good source of fuel for fusion reactions.

There are also several ores that are rare on the Overworld but exist in abundance on the Moon. In particular, the Moon contains large quantities of Titanium (in the form of Rutile Ore and Ilmenite Ore) and Tungsten (in the form of Scheelite Ore and Tungstate Ore).

Great for gathering large amounts of lava, and later on, oil.

Ender Pumps use RF to function.

Ender Tanks do not require power, but rather simply store fluid. All Ender Tanks on the same 'channel' (denoted by the three colors on the top) have the same contents, essentially allowing for instant long range transfer of fluid.

Try setting up one Ender Tank by an Ender Pump positioned over lava, and the other back up in your base. You'll have more lava than you know what to do with, without any boring bucketing.

You'll need a way to power the Ender Pump though... maybe a Magmatic Dynamo on site?

The tier one Microminers are useful for returning large amounts of basic materials to you, but its nothing you can't mine yourself.

However, the Quantum Flux returned by the Microminer is invaluable and cannot be obtained anywhere except via mining a Microverse.
Scatter a few around your base, and you can warp to anywhere you please!
Oxygen and Hydrazine combine together into Rocket Fuel.
Dimethylmine and Chloramine combine together into Hydrazine.

Methanol and Ammonia combine together to make Dimethylamine.

I know you're expecting a Breaking Bad joke here, but I don't walt to go for such low hanging fruit.
Hypochlorous Acid and Ammonia combine together to make Chloramine.

Hydrogen and Nitrogen combine together to make Ammonia.

Easiest way to get Nitrogen is to centrifuge Air, which will require you to build an Air Collector.
Oxygen, Hydrogen and Carbon combine together in a Chemical Reactor to make Methanol.

Water and Chlorine make Hypochlorous Acid. If you add Mercury, the yeild is much better.

§6Please note that Hypochlorous Acid and Hydrochloric Acid are different things.§r

Easiest source of Chlorine is electrolyzing Salt.

Easiest source of Mercury is electrolyzing Redstone.

Here comes the chemistry.

It might seem crazy right now, but at some point you'll want a dedicated Chemical Reactor for pretty much every chemical. You probably want to hold off on doing that until you've got a solid base of autocrafting though... it stings a lot less when you can just request 10 MV Chem Reactors from your AE2 system.

Fluid Export Busses are great for dumping the ingredients into the reactor. A Capacity Card will let you export five chemcials through a single bus.

You can slap a Fluid Storage Bus on the machine and just let it back up. It will end up with 64 buckets of each ingredient in the inputs, and 64 buckets of the output, then stop processing. Whenver you need some, your AE2 system will pull the needed fluid out and the machine will resume processing.

That sounds great (and it is, honestly) but there's a few things you need to remember. One, always reduce the priority of your Fluid Storage Busses, otherwise AE2 will put other random stuff inside the chemical reactor if there is ever room. And secondly, your AE2 system will SEE the inputs inside the chemical reactors, but not be able to access them (no more than you can pull any fluids in the input slots out using a bucket). This can be vexing for a few reasons, but its something you can work around.

There's a great deal of interesting content within Extra Utilities 2, and although most of it is not required for progression, you should still look through what it offers and build what interests you. In particular, the Angel Ring offers creative flight, and although some of the RF generators are not particularly good, others are quite competitive with the Dynamos. And of course, you can aim for the all powerful Rainbow Generator as you work towards endgame. All that and much more await, so explore away!

Mount the rocket with Spacebar, and hit 'C' to view the rocket's GUI. Click the Guidance Computer to open up its inventory, and put a Planet ID chip inside the computer. Then go to select destination and select Luna (the moon).

You're ready to blast off, but run through this checklist before you do.

- Make sure you're wearing your Space Suit (all four pieces) and that it has a full tank of Oxygen.

- Make sure you have a functional Telepad, with a local supply of RF power (like a capacitor bank), Dew of the Void, and a Chunk Loading Ward.

- Make sure you're carrying coordinates that lead to that Telepad.

- Make sure to bring your Coordinate Selector, blank Paper, and a second Telepad setup, also including RF Power, Dew of the Void and another Chunk Loading Ward.

After you've landed on the Moon's surface, set up your second Telepad. Code in the coordinates back to the Overworld into it. Then record your current coordinates. Teleport back home, and encode those coordinates into the Overworld Telepad. You can now teleport to the Moon freely!

There's a great deal of interesting content within Actually Additions, and although most of it is not required for progression, you should still look through what it offers and build what interests you. In particular, the Drill with all the upgrades is a fantasticly powerful mining tool, and even better is the Vertical Digger, which can effortlessly clear an entire vein for you. Phantomfaces, Auto Placers, Lava Factories, and much more await.
Barium is a rare ore inside Quartz veins.
The next electronic component. This one is a bit pricey, requiring Aluminium.

This compass will lead you to the nearest meteor impact.

Please note that the meteors might be buried underground.

When the compass is spinning wildly, you're right on top of the meteor.
Produces 4 RF/t for free, forever.

This quest, and the ones that follow it, are §cNOT REQUIRED§r for progression.

Only do them if you want to be able to explore the various planets offered by Advanced Rocketry and potentially build bases there, or in space.

Refer to the various high quality tutorials on AR available on youtube for specifics.
Your first MV hull is as good of a place as any to consider yourself graduated from LV.

Electrolyzers use electricity to separate items into their more basic components. For example, you can break down Water into Hydrogen Gas and Oxygen Gas, or break down Clay Dust into Sodium Dust, Silicon Dust, Lithium Dust, and Aluminium Dust.
Purified Galena, Purified Sphalerite and Sulfuric Acid can be used to make Tiny Piles of Indium.

betterquesting:10.name:8: The Fourth And Final Tier Four Circuits
betterquesting:10.desc:8: With all of the many components in place, its time to merge them together into a single circuit. Go ahead and craft a §aQuantum Circuit§r.
Arsenic can be obtained through the electrolysis of Cobaltite.
Radon will be needed in large quantities, and for now, you'll need to obtain it from Tier Two Microminer missions.
With all of the many components in place, its time to merge them together into a single circuit. Take these parts and combine them with three §aQuantum Circuits§r to craft a §aQuantum Processor§r.
No Description
The first tier of capacitors. These (or stronger versions) are required to make EnderIO machines run.

Mixes two dusts to make a third.

For now, you'll be using it to make Glowstone Dust and Energetic Blend.

Glowstone Dust is made from Phosphor Dust and Gold Dust.

Or you could gather it from the Nether.

Energetic Blend is made from Glowstone Dust and Redstone Dust.
Luminessence is used in a number of things, but right now, it will be a component in your Extended Crafting Tables.
Phosphorous Pentoxide and Water combine together into Phosphoric Acid.

Phosphate can be electrolyzed again into Phosphorous and Oxygen Gas.

Recombine them in the correct ratios inside a Chemical Reactor to get Phosphorous Pentoxide.
You can combine various items with a Blank Data Module for a completed Data Model that you can run inside the Simulation Chamber.
Man, that's a LOT of quests linked to this one.

Before you travel to the Moon, you'll want to set up a way to easily return.

Lay out nine of the Telepads in a 3x3 pattern. They should turn into a multiblock. While having some Paper in your inventory, use the Coordinate Selector to create a Location Printout of an area near the Telepad. Keep track of this Printout and make sure to bring it with you to the Moon!

Make sure the Telepad on the Overworld is ready to go. It needs power, a tank of Dew of the Void, and a Chunk Loading Ward (so it stays loaded while you're on the Moon). Bring the other nine Telepads with you when you go to the Moon, and once there, set up a similar layout. The one on the Moon will also need power, Dew of the Void, and a Chunk Loading Ward. Bring a solar panel as well to make sure it stays powered.

Once your Moon Telepad is up and running, put your Overworld coordinates into it. Then record your current location on the Moon with the Coordinate Selector. Teleport home, and put those coordinates into the Overworld Telepad. Now you can travel back and forth easily!

You might consider building a room dedicated to Telepad transit, both on the Overworld and to other Planets, and label them. You'll be visiting many other worlds soon enough.

Fluix is made the normal way. Check JEI for more information if you're not familiar.

The Energy Acceptor turns RF power into something that Applied Energistics can use. This power transmitted along all connected ME Cables and ME Conduits, as well as through Quartz Cable. Quartz Cable doesn't transmit information or count as a network connection, however.

The next step in the circuit grind.

You'll also need access to HSS-G ingots to make this machine.

Not a project for the faint of heart.

Make sure your power and circuit production are up to the challenge before you try to build this.

Notice that all numbers of required items are multiples of 12. This is to make an Assembly Line that's 12 units long, allowing for 12 inputs. 12 is enough to make a Fusion Reactor Controller Mk1, but you'll need an even longer Line for later projects.

The Fluid Input Hatches can replace any of the Steel Casings along the bottom outside except for the Casings touching the Output Bus. The Energy Input Hatches along the top can be replaced by Steel Casings, and you only need the one Energy Input Hatch (although you can add more if you want). The Input Buses along the bottom must be ULV tier, nothing else.

After such a tough megaproject in the Assembly Line, time for something nice and easy.

Just kidding.
You'll need at least Naquadrah Coil Blocks in your blast furnace to smelt Draconium.
Another good use for Helium.
You'll need an IV Precision Laser Engraver for this craft.
The culmination of so much effort.

Obtaining Grains of Infinity will require you to mine all the way down to Bedrock level.

Use Flint and Steel to light a fire (or many fires) and then wait for it to go out. There's a 50% chance of Grains Of Infinity to appear for every fire.

If you're creative, its possible to automate this with some of the later machines.

You'll need large quantities of Canola (for Bio Diesel) and Sugarcane (for Ethanol).

Of course, other crops will work as well, if you want to mix things up.
Just ignore the protesters outside your base.
Boron is obtained from a side effect of advanced methods of processing Lepidolite.

betterquesting:10.name:8: The Fourth And Final Tier Six Circuit
The Third and Final Tier Seven Circuit
The Second And Final Tier Eight Circuit
The First And Only Tier Nine Circuit

betterquesting:10.desc:8: Creating Draconium is a complex process, but you'll want to automate every step of it, since you'll be needing quite a lot of Draconium in the long run.
HV Batteries function the same as LV and MV, only requiring more resources to craft.

The full complexity of Nuclearcraft is far too much for the scope of this quest guide, so you're encouraged to watch a tutorial or read a guide online. For the purposes of this particular quest, you'll be building a cheap breeder reactor to works towards Plutonium.

First, set up your 56 Reactor Casings to encase a 3x3 cube shape of empty air. The Casings should only cover the faces of the interoir cube, not the edges or corners. You should have exactly the right number of Casings to encase a 3x3 space.

Now open a hole so you can look into the cube and set up the interior. The Reactor Cells will go in all 8 corners. Then the Lapis Coolers will go inbetween them, 4 on top layer and 4 on the bottom layer. At this point, the top and botom layers should have eight blocks each with an empty middle, and the middle layer fully empty. Then in the middle layer, place the 4 Graphite blocks on the corners, and the 4 Glowstone Coolers on the sides (so they touch both Lapis Coolers). Now the cube should be full, except for an empty column in the middle. The reactor will now be complete when you reseal it up with the Casings you removed to access the interior.

Finally, place the Fission Reactor Controller along any edge or corner of the reactor. Opening the Reactor Controller should let you know that the structure was properly formed, if not, go back and check what you did wrong.

If you don't want to mine Obsidian hand, consider using a Fluid Solidifier to turn Lava into Obsidian Blocks for you. The process is slow and energy intensive, though.

Its useful for lots of other things too of course. Look through the various molds to see what you can make.

Make sure its actually a mold, too. Extruder Plates look very similar to molds, but they don't work in anything but an Extruder.
The Glider is a great way to cross long distances, if you're so inclined.
Are you ready to go infinite?

With creative fluids and all the automation you hopefully set up for your first Infinity Catalyst, these ingots should be easy.

Well, not easy. But... reasonble.

You win.

Congratulations.

I hope you enjoyed playing Omnifactory.

Creative access to fluids.

With this, you have effecitvely infinite amounts of all fluid resources.

Despite that, the pack will still be fairly challenging to complete from here on out.

Infinite resources and power is nice, but its not everything.

A Grappling Hook is very useful in an urban enviroment.

There are lots of ways to upgrade and improve your Grappling Hook, so play around with it.
You can feed your Steam Boilers by hand for now. But if you want to get it fully automated, build an Infinite Water Source and hook it up by conduits to the bottom of your Boilers.
No hoops to jump through here. Smelt Wood Logs to get Charcoal. It will serve you well as a fuel source until you locate a vein of Coal.

A Rubber Mallet can be used to temporarily stop a machine from functioning. This is useful when you have two machines running and both are unable to keep going because of a lack of power... let one finish then turn the other one back on with a second hit from the mallet.

Useful to carry more stuff.

What more explanation are you expecting?
You'll need a Compressor for a variety of things, but probably most importantly is the ability to make plates from a single ingot.
You'll need an autoclave for many recipes involving gems. Certus Quartz Crystals are made here.
Lumberaxes will fully chop down a tree if you chop down the bottom block. Only Lumberaxes have this functionality, vanilla axes will not work for this.

Is it expensive? Yes. Is it worth it? Hell yes.

It doesn't start to shine until you get the good upgrades for it though, so maybe hold off for a while.
If you want to upgrade from the smaller ME Chest, you'll need a better screen.

Click a fluid with a single empty bucket on your cursor to fill it up with the fluid.

Also works with cells.

Storage Drawer Controllers are the central hub of any good storage system. They can pull from any drawers they are connected to (via other drawers, or drawer trims) within a 12 block cubic radius. This leads to a potential 25x25x25 area to connect drawers, centered on the controller.

Controller Slaves do not extend the range, but rather act as another access point to that controller - allowing you to push/pull from any of the drawers within range of the local Drawer Controller.
Huge amount of storage for a single item type. Use for things you have a lot of, such as stone, dirt and ores.
Great for automatically converting between Nuggets, Ingots and Blocks of metals, or simply storing massive amounts of things.

When making circuits, you'll need either molten Tin, or molten Soldering Alloy in the Assembler. Soldering Alloy is just Tin alloyed with Antimony, and the Assembler will only consume half as much Soldering Alloy as it would have consumed Tin per craft.

Tiny Piles of Antimony can be obtained by centrifuging Impure Tetrahedrite Dust or Impure Stibnite Dust. 9 tiny piles makes a dust.

Now that you have a Wiremill, you can turn one Copper Wire into four Fine Copper Wire. The recipes for Resistors, LV Motors and Vacuum Tubes all accept either type, so doing this extra processing step will make your Copper Ingots go four times further when making circuits. You'll be making a lot more circuits from here on out, so its definitely worthwhile to save your copper!

betterquesting:10.name:8: The Fourth And Final Tier Three Circuits
betterquesting:10.desc:8: With all of the many components in place, its time to merge them together into a single circuit. Go ahead and craft a §bNanocircuit§r.
A small appetizer, before the Omnium main couse.
Distinctly different from EnderIO's RF Capacitors, these are only useful as circuit components.

You can turn Plant Balls and other various sugary crops into Biomass with a Brewery. Biomassis the first step towards making Plastic (technically called 'Polyethylene').

The Brewery is a very very slow machine, and it requires almost no power. Building higher tier Breweries, or many LV ones, is recommended if you want to have a sufficient amount of Biomass.
Ethanol is produced from Biomass.

A Farming Station is an upgraded version of the Farmer. It requires more power, as well as tools, but it can handle more types of crops (like Sugarcane and Netherwart), and can be faster with better capacitors.
You'll need Chlorine at this point. You can get it from electrolyzing salt, among other sources.

EnderIO and Thermal alloys are a bit more expensive than the normal wires, but they come with the huge advantage of being lossless. Non-lossless  cables like Tin and Copper will bleed out energy for every block they travel, but not lossless ones.

The lossless cables for each tier are:

LV -    Conductive Iron Cables
MV -    Energetic Alloy Cables
HV -    Vibrant Alloy Cables
EV -    End Steel Cables
IV -     Lumium Cables
LuV -   Signalum Cables
ZPMV - Enderium Cables
UV -    Draconium Cables
MaxV - Omnium Cables

MV cables and higher are made in the Chemical Reactor. At MV, they're made with liquid Rubber and the cable, plus a circuit with the correct setting.

You can use unshielded Wires, and they'll conduct just as well as if they were covered. But they'll kill you if you touch them while power is passing through, so... yeah. Your call.

Mix together these two crushed gems along with Resonant Ender to make Dew of the Void, the fluid that will power interdimensional teleportation.

Please note that Dew of the Void goes great with Doritos.
An RF powered Chemical Reactor of sorts, used to produce EnderIO liquids.

The first step of soul crafting.

Needs tools to function placed in the right slots.
Not as common a component, but used in a number of critical machines.
One of the most expensive components, and used in a few powerful machines.
One of the rarest components, but needed for the Circuit Assembler.
With all of the many components in place, its time to merge them together into a single circuit. Take these parts and combine them with three §bNanocircuits§r to craft a §bNanoprocessor.
No Description

TE Dynamos can be upgraded to four additional tiers past the 'Basic' tier. This gives the dynamos a multiplier to the base power generation rate as follows:

Basic: 100%

Hardened: 150%

Reinforced: 250%

Signalum: 500%

Resonant: 1000%

Just like with Auxilliary Transmission Coils, the efficiency of the fuel remains the same, so the power comes faster, but consumes the same amount of fuel. However, upgrading also gives additional augment slots, which you can use to increase the dynamo's efficiency.
No Description

With all of the many components in place, its time to merge them together into a single circuit. Go ahead and craft a §6Primitive Circuit§r.

This is where your Worktable setups will really shine! With the patterns encoded into a Worktable (well, really over many Worktables), you'll be able to batch craft circuits quickly. You'll be making a LOT of circuits, so you might as well invest the time into making them easier.
No Description
No Description
No Description

It is recommended that you bookmark this link, it will likely help you as you continue to progress through the circuits.



https://i.imgur.com/vF5EDEi.png

These two dusts will be used in a variety of upcoming chemical reactions.

Both can be obtained in many ways, but one option for each is that Phosphorus is found in Apetite veins, and Sulfur is electrolyzed from Sphalerite (along with Gallium, very useful later on).
An alternative way to make many things from metal, a more efficient way to make things like Gears, and the only way to make certain things, like Large Pipes. You'll need them soon.

As you continue to progress, the Blast Furnace crafting times will continue to scale, and more advanced coils do not give speed bonuses, only allowing for the processing of more advanced materials. You'll need to get your infrastructure for smelting, as well as for power generation, up to snuff.

You don't need to get all four of these multiblocks completed and running just yet, but be prepared to expand.
For all your soul crafting needs.

Carry more stuff.

What more explanation are you expecting?

Carry even more stuff.

What more explanation are you expecting?

betterquesting:10.name:8: I Dont Need No Stinkin' Tower
betterquesting:10.desc:8: If you don't feel up to making a Distillation Tower just yet, you can get Ethanol via a single block Distillery. However, the Distillation Tower will be needed for petrochemical stuff like Oil later on... but its optional at least for a little while longer.

A good way to find a specific ore you're missing is the Block Module for your Scanner. Right click the Block Module against the ore you're searching for, then put it inside the Scanner and wander around scanning. The range is significantly longer than it is when using the modules which detect all ores, and you even have room for a second Range Module if you've got an Ender Pearl laying around.

You can combo this with buying ores you're missing from the shop to act as a 'sample', then find a full vein with the Block Module.
Most gears will require being smelted inside an Alloy Furnace using a Gear Mold, at least until you get an Extruder at MV power levels.

If you don't like the idea of mining out Oilsands veins, you can build an Oil Drilling Rig.

You'll need to provide it with power, Drilling Fluid, and a steady supply of pipes. The Pipes only have a 1% chance to have one be used up per bucket.

Place the Vertical Digger over an ore vein, feed it RF, and it will quickly rip up the entire vein for you.

For drills, you will need a Gregtech Drill (any LV drill will work), a Fluxbore (Reinforced tier is required) and an Actually Additions Drill (any color is fine, take out any augments you wish to keep).

The Gregtech Drill will not be consumed, but everything else will be.
Up to three Phantom Boosters can be placed atop the Vertical Digger to increase its area of effect.

Being able to fly is pretty sick. Its also pretty expensive.

Its probably a bit premature to consider a jetpack at this point, but if you really want to craft this bad boy, I won't stop you.

There's also a quest chain for EnderIO Jetpacks (starting with the Conductive Iron Jetpack). Eventually you'll need to make both, but not for a long time, so feel free to ignore at least one of these quest chains unless you really really like flying.
Better flying.

Even better flying.

You're not getting up to Resonant for a long time, just FYI.

Now that you have a Wiremill and a Compressor, you can consider starting to do Bounties. The Bounty Board has a global inventory containing quests to turn in specific items in exchange for Omnicoins. These quests have a fairly short duration, so make sure to stockpile the items that come up on them or else they'll expire before you can complete them.

With renewable Omnicoins, you should feel free to spend the ones you have on whatever ores you find yourself needing more of. Spend your coins!

This is an augment that will work in all dynamos. It increases the efficiency of the fuel being used inside the dynamo, increasing the power it generates. However, the rate of power generation remains the same, the fuel simply lasts longer. So while Fuel Catalyzers decrease the amount you'll need to go mining for Coal, they won't boost your production of electricity per second.

Each Fuel Catalyzer increases fuel efficiency by 15%, additively (so two will make fuel last 30% longer, three is 45% longer, etc).

This is an augment that will work in all dynamos. It greatly increases the rate at which the dynamo generates electricity, while also increasing fuel consumption at the same rate. In theory, the same effect could be achieved simply by building additional dynamos, but using Auxilliary Transmission Coils is cheap and effective way to greatly boost your power production, so long as you don't mind losing out on the small efficiency boost to the fuel provided by Fuel Catalyzers.

Each Auxilliary Transmission Coil increases both power production and fuel consumption by 100%, additively (so the second is 200%, third is 300%, etc).

As you continue to progress, the Blast Furnace crafting times will continue to scale, and more advanced coils do not give speed bonuses, only allowing for the processing of more advanced materials. You'll need to get your infrastructure for smelting, as well as for power generation, up to snuff.

You don't need to get all eight of these multiblocks completed and running just yet, but plan to at some point in the future. You'll have lots of spare coils soon enough, as you upgrade.

This will also add two additional upgrade slots.

LEU-235 (which stands for Low Enriched Uranium 235) is made from 8 units of of U-238, and 1 unit of U-235. Make some and then run it through the Fission Reactor to deplete it. The RF power that is generated is nice, but the primary goal is actually to obtain the depleted fuel and process it.

Depleted LEU 235 Fuel should be centrifuged to give back some U-238, as well as a bit of Neptunium and Plutonium.

The End Game tab may be open for you. If its not, it will be soon. This might seem a bit premature, but it has a reason.

These are quests for a full stack of many of the materials in the game. Those are the materials you'll need to synthesize Omnium, the basic end game resource. Its the pack's way of letting you know what materials you should be prepared to mass produce as you approach the end.

Of course, its not necessary or even advisable to try to finish up all of these quests the moment they become available. Some will be incredibly easy (like Iron and Copper), others will be brutally grindy at early tech levels. The rewards are all the same: 25 Omnicoins each, so use your best judgement on which ones to complete and which to ignore for later.

9 Thorium Dust can be turned into TBU Fuel.

Use the TBU fuel in your reactor and let it run until its depleted. The RF power that is generated is nice, but the primary goal is actually to obtain the depleted fuel and process it.

Depleted TBU Fuel will give you U-233, as well as some Neptunium.

Dealing with Nuclear Fuel in any reasonable amount of time will require significant infrastructure. Converting your raw Uranium 238 and Uranium 235 ingots into processed materials useful for fission reactions will require running them through the Thermal Centrifuge, with very long processing times. Higher tiered Thermal Centrifuges will substantially cut down on this time, as will running several machines in parellel.

Processing your depleted fuels will require similar work in a Centrifuge. And again, the processing times are significant, so consider using as high of a power tier as you feel you can afford to.

Using only the results from Thorium fission, it will take two batches of Depleted TBU Fuel to make your first LEN fuel. Of course, higher order reactions also will result in small amounts of Neptunium that you can work with as well.

Depleted LEN 236 gives a small bit of Neptunium back, as well as some Plutonium and Americium.

Uranium 233 can only be aquired from the fission of Thorium Fuels.

LEU-233 is made from one U-233 and eight U-238.

Depleted LEU-233 will give you various types of Plutonium and some Americium.

Depleted LEP-239 will give you some Curium for further enrichment.

Richer blends of Plutonium will give better results, but make sure your reactor can handle the heat.
Depleted Curium results in Berklium and Californium.

Americium 242 and 243 make LEA 242 Fuel.

There's also Americium 241, but this is only useful for making RTGs or decaying down into Neptunium.

Depleted LEA 242 will return large amounts of Curium.

Now that you have all the basic building blocks of nuclear fission, you'll need to start creating breeding chains to mass produced stabilized versions of each element, for the synthesis of Omnium.

Experiment around with larger reactors that can handle highly enriched fuels.

You'll need to build a fair few reactors to complete this task in any reasonable amount of time.

A Simulation Chamber allows you to farm mobs in a totally enviormentally (and server) friendly way!

Simulated mobs can even be used to provide you with many of the basic resources you'll need, although it requires a fairly substantial amount of power and time invested before you start seeing solid returns.

Provide your Simulation Chamber with RF power and Pulsating Polymer Clay. Then insert a Data Module of your choice. The Simulation Chamber will consume Polymer Clay and a decent amount of power to begin simulating mob kills. This will generate Overworldian Matter and may occasionally provide you with Pristine Matter.

Overworldian Matter can be eaten to gain experience, or can be combined with other materials to obtain drops from Overworld mobs. With these drops, you can then create Data Modules for other mob types as well.
String and Coal Dust can be baked together into a Carbon Mesh in an Alloy Furnace. Combine that with Pulsating Dust to get a Pulsating Mesh.
Simulating mob kills will occasionally result in Pristine matter of that mob's type. Putting Pristine mob matter into a Loot Fabricator will allow you to obtain mob drops from that mob.

There's no rush to get these all done and leveled up. But they do provide a good source of some of the basic resources in exchange for RF. Look at what the Pristine Matter for each mob provides and let the ones you're interested in run when you have extra power and are doing something else.
You can feed the Steam Dynamo with water by hand, but you'll get sick of that soon enough. An Infinite Water Source will take care of that for you.

Overworldian Matter and Netherrack can be crafted into Hellish Matter.

Netherrack is obtained by combining a Dust Block and Lava in a Chemical Reactor.
Just as with Overworldian mob data, there's no huge rush or need to focus on these. Just run them while you work on other projects.
Hellish Matter and Ender Pearl can be crafted into Extraterrestrial Matter.

Some of these simulations will start to consume tremendous amounts of power at this point, so if you're finding it a struggle, don't be afraid to hold off on progressing through these data models until a later time.

The Wrench is used with Gregtech machines.

You can see which mod a machine is from with the blue text at the bottom of its tooltip.
